string-array.name: culture_info
string-array.item:
"Japanese 'Nihongo/ 日本語' is spoken by over 130 million people.
Japanese has 4 writing systems. These are Kanji 漢字, Hiragana ひらがな, Katakana カタカナ, and Roomaji.
There are 46 Hiragana characters, 46 Katakana characters and thousands of Kanji characters.
Hiragana are usually used to write native words and grammar particles, eg. apple -りんご/ ringo.
Katakana are usually used to write foreign words adopted into Japanese, eg. coffee - コーヒー/ koohii.
Kanji characters are Chinese characters that were adopted into Japanese and can be used to represent many Japanese words, eg. Japanese - 日本語/ にほんご/ nihongo.
Roomaji is the standard romanisation of the Japanese language.
It is easier to start learning Hiragana and Katakana before you attempt Kanji. It takes a knowledge of about 1800 kanji to be able to read a newspaper."

"This is said before starting a meal or when receiving something.
Meaning: I humbly receive"

"Meaning: Long time no see
Informal: Hisashiburi"

"This is said after a meal as a sign of appreciation. It can be said to the cook/restaurant owner or person who paid for the meal.
Informal: gochisousama"

"This is said when answering the phone.
Meaning: hello"

"This is said when a person returns home.
Tadaima is said by the returning person.
Meaning: I'm home
Okaeri nasai is said by the person who is already at home.
Informal: okaeri
Meaning: Welcome home"

"This is said when a person leaves home/goes out.
Itte kimasu is said by the person leaving.
Meaning: I'm going (and coming back)
Itterasshai is said by the person who is staying.
Meaning: Have a good time/See you later"

"This is a polite expression said when a person finishes work or leaves the office before other colleagues. It is usually said by a subordinate to a superior.
Meaning: I'm leaving first
Informal: osaki ni"

"This is used to express appreciation for a person's hard work when they leave. It doesn't readily translate into English as there is no exact equivalent. It is a polite expression said when a person leaves or finishes work or a task. It is said by the other people who witness the person leaving or finishing.
Informal: otsukare"

"This is a polite expression said when someone is entering someone else's home or is interrupting someone else.
Meaning: I'm interrupting you"

"Used as a greeting in Osaka and the Kansai area.
Meaning: How is business going?"
"This is a polite expression used by a shop clerk/restaurant worker to welcome a customer. It is usually said when the customer enters the shop/restaurant."

"Common adjective expressions you may hear said quite often, particularly by young woman or girls:
Sugoi! - that's great
Saikou! - that's the best
Saitei - that's the worst
Kawaii! - that's cute
Kakkoii - he's/that's cool"
"One of the 'sankei' or three views of Japan, Amanohashidate is a picturesque pine covered sandbar in the northern part of Kyoto Prefecture."
Beppu is a city well known for its hotsprings (温泉 onsen). Located in Oita Prefecture on Kyuushuu island it is home to the eight hells of Beppu which are eight famous hotsprings.
Himeji castle , located in Himeji City, Hyogo Prefecture is the largest castle in Japan. It was first built in 1346 and castle and fort comprises of 83 buildings with advanced defenses.
Ishigaki Jima is a beautiful island at the bottom of the Okinawa island chain.
"Kinkakuji or the 'Golden Pavillion Temple' is a temple in Kyoto city. It covered in a layer of Japanese lacquer and gold leaf."
"One of the 'sankei' or three views of Japan, Matsuyama is a group of 260 islands (島 shima) covered in pine (松 matsu) in Miyagi Prefecture."

"One of the 'sankei' or three views of Japan, Miyajima is a shrine (神社 jinja) on an island in Hiroshima Prefecture. It is famous for its floating torii gate which becomes half submerged when the tide comes in. Miyajima is a short ferry ride from Hiroshima."

Nara Park (公園 kouen) is home to several temples and shrines along with over 1000 wild deer (シカ shika). There are numerous stalls that sell senbei crackers for people to feed the deer with. Todaiji is one the main temples in Nara Park and houses a giant 15 meter high bronze buddha statue.
Nikko shrine is a shinto shrine located in Tochigi Prefecture near Tokyo. It was first built in 1617 during the Edo period.
The Shikoku Pilgrimage (遍路道 henromichi) is a series of 88 temples on Shikoku the smallest of the 4 major islands of Japan.
Tsukiji Fish Market is the biggest fish and seafood market in the world. Go early in the morning to try some very fresh sushi.
Katsudon is a bowl of steaming rice with deep fried pork cutlet (tonkatsu), egg, sliced scallions and sauce.

"Katsuo Tataki is raw bonito fillets seared on the outside and served with onions, spring onions, garlic, perilla and covered with a ponzu, sauce containing soy sauce, vinegar and citrus juice. Katsuo Tataki is a dish originally from the Tosa region of Shikoku."
Okonomiyaki is a savoury pancake filled with different kinds of meat, seafood and vegetables. It is usually covered in a sauce, mayonnaise, katsuobushi and aonori.
"Oyakodon is a bowl of steaming rice topped with chicken, egg, sliced shallots, onions and sauce. Oyako means 'parent and child' and don means 'bowl of rice'."

"Famous the world over. These are some of the types of sushi you will find in Japan. Inarizushi - sushi encased in a fried tofu pouch. Makizushi - Means rolled sushi and is wrapped in a sheet of dried seaweed. Futomaki 'thick roll' is a thick type of makizushi. Hosomaki 'thin roll' is a a thin type. Temaki 'hand roll' is sushi wrapped in a small hand size sheet of dried seaweed and can be filled with whatever ingredients you wish. Nigiri zushi 'hand pressed' sushi is an rice shaped into an egg shaped mould and then covered with or without a dollop of wasabi and then strips of fish or seafood."

Takoyaki is a grilled ball shaped snack filled with a mixture of minced octopus, ginger and batter and then covered with sauce, Japanese mayonaise, dried fish flakes (katsuo bushi). This snack originally comes from Osaka.
Unadon is fresh water eel (鰻 unagi) grilled in a sweet soy sauce based sauce and served on a bed of steaming rice. The Day of the Ox is a special day in summer when unagi is usually eaten.

"Yakitori is grilled chicken on a sticked. 'yaki' means grilled, and 'tori' means bird . There are many varieties of yakitori including toriniku(white chicken flesh), negima(chicken and spring onions), nankotsu(chicken cartiledge, and tsukune cheezu (minced chicken balls with melted cheese in the middle)."
Zaru soba is cold soba (buckwheat) noodles that are dipped in a mixture of tsuyu sauce, spring onions and wasabi.
